    dayNumber: 20,
    whyThis: "On Day 18, you wrote three versions of your story — polished, honest, and raw. Over the past two days, you've also separated the structural from the personal and sorted systemic from individual factors. Now you have enough material to write a version of your story you can actually stand behind. Not the performance version. Not the self-punishing version. A version that's true — one that acknowledges what happened structurally, what was personal, what you learned, and where you're headed. Narrative therapy research by Michael White and David Epston found that the stories we tell about difficult experiences shape how we relate to them going forward. A story that's both honest and livable — one you can say without apologizing, minimizing, or over-explaining — may help you move through conversations about your job loss without it costing you energy every time.",
    instruction: "In the left column ('Story Element'), you'll find the building blocks of your refined narrative — what happened, why, what was structural, what was personal, what you learned, and what's next. In the right column, write your version of each element. Keep each one to 1-2 sentences. When all rows are filled, read them in order — that's your story. Test it: can you say it without apologizing? Without minimizing? Without over-explaining? If any part still feels forced, edit it until it's yours.",
