    dayNumber: 22,
    whyThis: "Week 4 — the final week — begins with looking forward. Over the past three weeks you've mapped what was disrupted, examined your beliefs and identity, named your saboteurs, surfaced your values, collected evidence of competence, and written a story you can stand behind. That's a lot of looking back and looking inward. Now it's time to look ahead. Something may have been quietly emerging during this process — an interest, a direction, a curiosity you've been dismissing as impractical or 'not serious.' This exercise creates space for that. The Venn diagram maps what genuinely interests you against what you're actually capable of. The overlap — where curiosity meets competence — is worth paying attention to. It might not be a full career plan yet. It might just be a thread worth pulling. Stanford psychologist John Krumboltz's planned happenstance theory suggests that career breakthroughs often come from following unexpected interests, not from rigid planning.",
    instruction: "Drag each item into one of three zones: 'What Interests Me' (left) for things you're genuinely curious about — even if they seem impractical, 'What I'm Good At' (right) for capabilities and strengths you trust, or the overlap (middle) for things that live in both — genuine curiosity backed by real capability. Use 'Add' to include your own interests or skills that aren't listed. When you're done, focus on the overlap zone. That's where emerging directions are both authentic and feasible. What thread would you pull if no one were watching? Pick one item from the overlap zone and take a single small action on it this week — a conversation, a search, 30 minutes of exploration. Not a commitment, just a pull on the thread.",
