    tags: ["core-parachute"],
    dayNumber: 25,
    whyThis: "This exercise brings together work from Day 4 (where you first identified your saboteurs) and Day 12 (where you caught them in action during the week). You know which voices show up. You know when they get loudest. Now you build if-then contingency plans — so that next time the voice fires, you have a pre-planned response instead of getting hijacked. Peter Gollwitzer's research on implementation intentions at New York University found that if-then plans ('when X happens, I will do Y') may roughly double follow-through compared to general intentions, because they create an automatic link between trigger and response. Instead of relying on willpower in the moment, you're programming the response in advance. Each saboteur card below represents one of your top patterns. For each one, you'll name the trigger, what the voice says, and what you'll do instead. In the sandbox, the saboteur data is representative — in the live program, this would pull from your Day 4 and Day 12 responses.",
    instruction: "For each saboteur card, fill in three fields: the trigger (when does this voice show up?), the script (what does it say to you?), and the counter-move (what will you do instead next time?). The counter-move should be specific and doable — not 'be more positive' but 'take three breaths and ask: is this voice helping me right now?' When all cards are filled, read each if-then plan out loud. Speaking it may help it stick. These plans carry forward — you'll reference them when pressure hits.",
