    dayNumber: 27,
    whyThis: "On Day 20, you refined your story into a version you could stand behind. Today you test it under pressure — because the real test of a narrative isn't writing it in a quiet moment. It's holding onto it when a saboteur voice jumps in mid-sentence, when someone asks an unexpected question, or when your body tenses up and the polished version evaporates. This exercise uses three panels to map what happens when your narrative meets stress. The first panel is the saboteur's version — what the story becomes when your inner critic takes over. The second is the centered version — the one you refined on Day 20. The third is the repair version — what you say to get back on track when you lose your center mid-telling. Having all three visible at once may help you see how close the centered and saboteur versions actually are, and where the repair moves live.",
    instruction: "Write three versions. Panel 1: 'The Saboteur's Version' — how does the story sound when your inner critic is driving? What gets added, exaggerated, or minimized? Panel 2: 'The Centered Version' — the story you refined on Day 20, the one that's true without being punishing. Panel 3: 'The Repair Version' — what do you say to yourself to get back to center when you feel the saboteur taking over mid-conversation? When all three are written, practice the centered version out loud. Notice where your body tenses — that's where the saboteur waits.",
