    primitive: "splitAnnotator",
    tags: ["core-parachute"],
    dayNumber: 29,
    whyThis: "Tomorrow is the last day. Today you write a letter to yourself 90 days from now. This isn't journaling — it's a time capsule. Research by Hal Hershfield at UCLA suggests that people who feel connected to their future selves make better decisions in the present, because the future self stops feeling like a stranger. Right now, you know things that future-you may forget: what the hard days felt like, what you learned about your patterns, what values you committed to, what your saboteurs sound like. In 90 days, the urgency of this period will have faded — and with it, some of the clarity. This letter anchors what you've learned so you can come back to it when you need to. The prompts below give your letter structure so it captures the specific, actionable insights — not just general reflections.",
    instruction: "Each row is a section of your letter. In the left column, you'll see the prompt — what this part of the letter addresses. In the right column, write your response directly to your future self. Be specific: name the saboteurs, reference the values, describe the commitments. 'Remember to be brave' is forgettable. 'When the Judge shows up before a networking call, take three breaths and remember that the evidence file is real' is something future-you can actually use. When all sections are filled, read the letter from top to bottom. This is what you're carrying forward.",
