    dayNumber: 2,
    whyThis: "Day 2 is about meeting the inner voices that get louder when you're being evaluated. Under PIP pressure, most people develop automatic protection strategies — a people-pleaser who agrees to everything, a hyper-achiever who overworks to prove worth, a controller who tries to manage every variable. These patterns are sometimes called saboteurs — a concept from Shirzad Chamine's Positive Intelligence framework. They're not enemies. They were once survival strategies that may now be working against you. The Pleaser keeps you safe by avoiding conflict, but on a PIP it might mean you never push back on unclear expectations. The Hyper-Vigilant keeps you alert, but under a PIP it turns every email into a threat. Naming these patterns is the first step toward noticing them in real time instead of being run by them. You'll also identify your default stress direction — a concept from psychoanalyst Karen Horney: do you move toward people (seeking approval), against them (fighting back), or away (withdrawing)? This adds a second layer of self-awareness that becomes useful throughout the program.",
    instruction: "Below are six common saboteur patterns that show up under PIP pressure. Sort each card into one of three buckets: 'Recognize strongly' for patterns running your behavior right now, 'Shows up sometimes' for occasional visitors, and 'Doesn't apply' for patterns that aren't yours. Use 'Add a card' to name a voice you recognize that isn't listed. After sorting, take a moment in your journal to write about your top 2-3: what does each voice say to you, and when does it get loudest? Also note your stress direction — toward, against, or away.",
