    tags: ["core-jetstream"],
    dayNumber: 4,
    whyThis: "Day 4 is about separating what the PIP actually says from what your mind has added to it. When we're under evaluation threat, the brain automatically layers meaning on top of neutral words — turning 'needs improvement in communication' into 'they think I'm incompetent and they're building a case to fire me.' This is a normal threat response, not a character flaw. But the gap between the document and the story matters enormously for how you respond. Marshall Rosenberg's Nonviolent Communication framework draws a sharp line between observation (what actually happened) and evaluation (the meaning we attach). Cognitive therapy makes a similar distinction. By physically separating the PIP's actual words from your interpretation, you may find that some of your worst fears are stories your saboteur wrote — and some are grounded in real concerns that deserve a real plan. Both are useful to see clearly.",
    instruction: "In the left column ('The Document'), write what the PIP actually says — the specific requirements, metrics, timelines, or behavioral expectations. Verbatim, just the words on the page. In the right column ('The Story'), write the interpretation your mind has layered on top — catastrophizing, assumptions about intent, mind-reading, minimizing. Use the tags to mark each story as: 'catastrophizing,' 'mind-reading,' 'minimizing,' or 'could be accurate.' When you're done, look at the two columns side by side. The left column is actionable. The right column is what your saboteur does with the document. Which saboteur authored most of Column 2? Pick one item you tagged 'could be accurate' and write a concrete next step to verify it — a question you could ask your manager, a fact you could check, or a person you could consult.",
