    id: "jetstream-day-5",
    name: "Three Columns (Valid / Political / Cannot Tell)",
    modality: "cognitive",
    originator: "Mindcraft / All Minds on Deck",
    primitive: "cardSort",
    tags: ["core-jetstream"],
    dayNumber: 5,
    whyThis: "Not all feedback on a PIP is created equal. Some of it points to genuine development areas — things you'd want to work on even without the PIP. Some of it reflects organizational dynamics: a manager style mismatch, shifting expectations after a reorg, a personality conflict dressed up as a performance issue. And some of it sits in uncomfortable ambiguity — you genuinely cannot tell whether it's about you or the system. Most approaches to feedback push you toward a binary: either accept it all (the Hyper-Achiever's move) or reject it all (the Victim's move). This exercise resists that. The three-column sort — Valid, Political, Cannot Tell — forces nuance. The 'Cannot Tell' column is the real work. It's where honest self-assessment lives, in the space between self-blame and self-excuse. Sitting with ambiguity is uncomfortable, but research on decision-making under uncertainty suggests that tolerance of ambiguity may lead to better outcomes than premature certainty.",
    instruction: "Each card represents a piece of feedback from your PIP. Sort them into three buckets: 'Valid' for genuine development areas (things you'd agree with if a coach you respected said the same thing), 'Political' for organizational dynamics that aren't really about your performance, and 'Cannot Tell' for feedback where your self-protective instincts and your honest self-assessment give different answers. Use 'Add a card' to include specific feedback from your own PIP. When you're done, notice the sorting pattern — the Victim fills 'Political,' the Hyper-Achiever fills 'Valid,' the Avoider puts everything in 'Cannot Tell.' Which saboteur influenced your sorting? Pick one card from the 'Valid' column and write one specific action you'll take this week to address it. Valid feedback you act on is your strongest PIP defense.",
