    dayNumber: 9,
    whyThis: "Before Week 2 introduces the communication framework, this exercise surfaces what you're actually holding back. There's probably something you'd say to your manager if there were no consequences — something honest, maybe raw, that your saboteur edits before you finish the thought. James Pennebaker's expressive writing research at the University of Texas suggests that writing what you'd actually say — without the filter — may reduce the emotional charge it carries. This isn't about sending anything. It's about seeing what's underneath the performance you're maintaining at work. The gap between what you want to say and what you actually say reveals your communication pattern under pressure — and that becomes the starting material for next week's exercises.",
    instruction: "The dialogue has three turns. Turn 1 ('The Unfiltered Version'): write what you would say to your manager about the PIP if there were absolutely no consequences. Don't edit yourself. Turn 2 ('The Saboteur's Edit'): write how your saboteur would change that message — what it would soften, delete, or rephrase to keep you safe. Name which saboteur is doing the editing. Turn 3 ('What This Reveals'): look at the gap between Turn 1 and Turn 2. What need is hiding in the unfiltered version that the saboteur won't let you express? Write about that need — it's the material you'll work with next week.",
