    id: "jetstream-day-11",
    name: "Communication Under Pressure — Part 2: The Check-In Plan",
    modality: "relational",
    originator: "Mindcraft / All Minds on Deck",
    primitive: "dialogueSequence",
    tags: ["core-jetstream"],
    dayNumber: 11,
    whyThis: "Yesterday you mapped the gap between what you need and what you say. Today you use that awareness to prepare for your next PIP check-in — so you walk in with something centered to say instead of something reactive. The exercise uses the same NVC framework (Observation, Feeling, Need, Request) but applies it forward: what do you want your manager to know, what do you need from this meeting, and what's your specific request? The key move is writing two versions side by side — the saboteur's version (what your pattern would produce on autopilot) and the centered version (what your grounded self would say). Tara Mohr's distinction between the inner critic and the inner mentor is useful here: the critic performs safety, the mentor speaks from clarity. Seeing both versions on paper makes the choice visible. Research on cognitive rehearsal suggests that mentally practicing a conversation may improve actual performance — especially when the practice includes both the default pattern and the alternative.",
    instruction: "The dialogue sequence has four turns. Turn 1 ('One Observation'): write one specific, factual thing to share in your next check-in — not a defense, not an apology, just an observation (e.g., 'I completed X, Y, and Z since our last meeting'). Turn 2 ('One Need'): write one thing you need from this meeting — clarity, resources, timeline adjustment — expressed directly, not wrapped in an apology. Turn 3 ('The Saboteur's Version'): rewrite Turns 1 and 2 the way your saboteur would say them. Notice what it adds, softens, or removes. Turn 4 ('The Centered Version'): write the final version you'll actually use. Practice saying it out loud until it sounds like you — not a script, but your voice.",
