    whyThis: "The PIP may not stay at work. Under sustained pressure, stress spills into your closest relationships — showing up as specific, predictable patterns. John Gottman at the University of Washington calls them the Four Horsemen: criticism, contempt, defensiveness, and stonewalling. Each one has a specific antidote. This applies to partners, friends, family, and colleagues. The goal is to spot where PIP stress is activating these patterns so you can intervene before they do damage. The exercise below teaches each pattern and its repair move.",
    instruction: "Below are cards describing specific behaviors — some are horsemen, some are their antidotes. Sort each card into the horseman it belongs to: 'Criticism,' 'Contempt,' 'Defensiveness,' or 'Stonewalling.' Cards describing antidotes go into a fifth bucket: 'Antidotes.' After sorting, flip each antidote card to see which horseman it counters and how to practice it. In your journal, write about: which horseman is showing up most in your relationships right now? With whom? And which one antidote will you commit to practicing this week?",
