    dayNumber: 14,
    whyThis: "Day 14 closes Week 2 by naming the decision most people on a PIP are quietly avoiding: fight to stay or prepare to leave. You may not be ready to choose — and that's fine. But naming the fork, and seeing the forces pulling you in each direction, can reduce the low-grade anxiety that comes from holding an unnamed decision. Kurt Lewin's force field analysis — a foundational tool in organizational psychology — makes this visible by mapping the driving and restraining forces on each side. Some of those forces are grounded in evidence (your Reading the Room assessment from Day 6, your optionality ratings from Day 13). Others are driven by your saboteur — the Pleaser arguing to try harder, the Victim arguing it's hopeless, the Avoider arguing to think about it later. Seeing which forces are evidence-based and which are pattern-driven may help you think more clearly about what information you still need to make this decision.",
    instruction: "The force field has two sides. On the left ('Stay and Meet the PIP'), list every force driving you in that direction — stability, income, proving something, fear of the unknown, genuine development opportunity. On the right ('Prepare to Leave'), list every force pulling you that way — agency, relief, self-respect, better opportunities, exhaustion with the process. Rate each force's strength from 1-5. Then tag each one: 'evidence-based' for forces grounded in real data, or 'saboteur-driven' for forces your pattern is generating. When the map is complete, notice the balance. You don't need to decide today — but name the fork.",
