    whyThis: "The patterns that show up under PIP pressure don't stay at work. John Gottman's Four Horsemen — criticism, contempt, defensiveness, and stonewalling — were identified in relationship research, but they activate in any sustained threat state. Under PIP stress, you've been managing how you communicate at work all week (Day 10-11 NVC work, Day 12 Gottman sorting). But the cost of that management often shows up at home, where the filter comes off. You might snap at your partner over a small thing (criticism). Roll your eyes when they don't understand why you're stressed (contempt). Justify yourself when they ask a simple question (defensiveness). Or shut down entirely after a long day (stonewalling). This exercise takes the Four Horsemen from Day 12 and applies them specifically to your personal relationships. The antidotes are different at home than at work — you don't need NVC with your partner, you need warmth, repair, and the ability to say 'I'm having a hard day' instead of acting it out.",
