    whyThis: "Week 3 opens by examining how accurately you're assessing your own competence right now — because under PIP pressure, the answer is probably 'not very.' David Burns identified five distortion patterns especially relevant during a PIP: (1) Overgeneralization — 'I failed at X, therefore I fail at everything'; (2) Mental filter — focusing only on what went wrong; (3) Disqualifying the positive — 'That went well but it was easy'; (4) Magnification — blowing up failures, shrinking successes; (5) Labeling — 'I am incompetent' instead of 'I received specific feedback.' This exercise walks you through a three-step process for each distorted thought: say what you're thinking, identify which distortion filter is operating, then rewrite the thought accurately — not positively, accurately.",
    instruction: "Work through 3 rounds. In each round: Step 1 — write the distorted thought exactly as your mind produces it. Step 2 — name which of Burns' five filters is distorting it (Overgeneralization, Mental Filter, Disqualifying the Positive, Magnification, or Labeling). Step 3 — rewrite the thought accurately. Not optimistically — proportionally. The difference between distorted and accurate is where the saboteur lives. Carry the three accurate reframes with you this week. When you catch the distorted thought running, replace it with the proportional version — out loud if alone, internally if not.",
