    whyThis: "You've been tracking your saboteur patterns for over two weeks now. This exercise steps back to see the bigger picture: what has the pattern actually cost you? It's one thing to know 'I have a Pleaser pattern.' It's another to see concretely that the Pleaser made you agree to three unrealistic deadlines, avoid two necessary conversations, and absorb stress that showed up as irritability with your partner. Making the cost visible transforms abstract self-awareness into concrete motivation. The saboteur is not irrational — it runs a cost-benefit analysis. But that analysis is often outdated. The protection it provides (avoiding rejection, avoiding helplessness, avoiding pain) was calibrated for a different time. The cost, however, is current and real. In the live program, this exercise would pull your actual saboteur log data from Weeks 1-2. In the sandbox, representative data is shown — edit it to match your experience.",
    instruction: "The heatmap maps your top saboteur across four cost dimensions: frequency of activation (how often), professional cost (what it made you do or avoid at work), relational cost (how it showed up at home), and payoff (what it protects you from that feels scarier than all these costs). Tap each cell to rate the intensity from 0-5. Right-click to add specific examples — concrete moments, not abstractions. When the map is complete, look for the hottest area. That's where the pattern is doing the most damage. In your journal, answer: the saboteur's payoff — what it protects you from — is it still a real threat, or an old one? Pick the saboteur with the highest total cost. The next time it fires this week, try responding to the payoff directly: 'I see you trying to protect me from [the thing]. That threat is not as real as it was when you started.'",
