    id: "jetstream-day-19",
    name: "Boundary Architecture",
    modality: "relational",
    originator: "Mindcraft / All Minds on Deck",
    primitive: "cardSort",
    tags: ["core-jetstream"],
    dayNumber: 19,
    whyThis: "When you're on a PIP, there's enormous pressure to say yes to everything — to prove you're cooperative, committed, willing to do whatever it takes. But agreeing without limits is a trap. It leads to burnout that undermines the very performance the PIP is measuring. It also trains your manager to expect compliance rather than competence. Boundaries are not rebellion — they're architecture. They define what you will engage with fully, what you'll engage with on adjusted terms, and what crosses a line you won't cross. This exercise sorts PIP requirements into three categories: 'Will Do' (legitimate, actionable), 'Will Do With a Boundary' (vague or unrealistic, needs negotiation), and 'Will Not Do' (crosses ethical, personal, or professional lines). For the middle category, you'll write a negotiation statement using the NVC framework from Day 10. The saboteur check at the end is important: the Pleaser puts everything in 'Will Do,' the Controller puts too much in 'Will Not Do,' and the Victim claims everything is unfair.",
    instruction: "Each card represents a common PIP requirement or expectation. Sort them into three buckets: 'Will Do' for legitimate requirements you can commit to fully, 'Will Do With a Boundary' for items that need adjustment (vague expectations, unrealistic timelines, scope that requires resources you don't have), and 'Will Not Do' for anything that crosses an ethical, personal, or professional line. Use 'Add a card' to include requirements from your actual PIP. For each card in the 'With a Boundary' bucket, click to add a negotiation note using the NVC format: 'I observe [the requirement]. I need [clarity/resources/timeline]. I request [specific adjustment].' Practice saying one boundary statement out loud. Does it sound like you?",
