    dayNumber: 20,
    whyThis: "Day 20 zooms out from your inner patterns to the system your PIP exists within. PIPs serve two different purposes: genuine development (specific coaching, real resources) or termination documentation (vague requirements, moving goalposts). Sometimes both simultaneously. When you're inside one, it's easy to collapse into personal shame. But many PIPs reflect structural dynamics — reorgs, budget pressures, shifting expectations. Amy Edmondson's research at Harvard suggests that when psychological safety collapses under performance threat, performance itself declines — a self-reinforcing cycle. Separating structural from personal doesn't let you off the hook — it gets the story right.",
    instruction: "In the left column ('Factor'), list everything that contributed to your PIP — both structural and personal. Pre-filled examples include common organizational factors (reorg, management change, shifting expectations, company-wide PIP pattern) and personal factors (specific skill gaps, behavioral feedback). Edit these to match your situation and add your own. In the right column ('What's Personal About This'), note what — if anything — is genuinely about your individual performance. Tag each row: 'structural' for factors outside your control, 'personal' for factors within it, or 'mixed' for tangled situations. When you're done, count the tags. Most people carry far more personal shame than the facts warrant. For every row tagged 'structural,' practice this reframe: 'This is not about my worth — this is about the system.' Choose one structural factor and share it with a trusted person this week.",
