    whyThis: "Day 21 closes Week 3 with a status check on both tracks you've been holding since Day 14's Fork exercise. Track A is meeting the PIP requirements — deliverables, metrics, behavioral changes. Track B is optionality — the financial, legal, professional, and relational resources you're building in parallel. Most people under PIP pressure collapse into one track: either all-in on compliance ('if I just work hard enough they'll keep me') or all-in on exit ('it's hopeless, I should just leave'). Both are fear-driven. Strategic energy allocation means honestly assessing where each track stands and deciding — based on evidence, not anxiety — where your energy goes this week. This is the concept of dual-track operating: meeting the PIP requirements AND preparing for the possibility that it doesn't work out. It's not disloyalty. It's agency. The person who can walk away negotiates differently than the person who can't.",
    instruction: "The force field has two sides. On the left ('Track A: Meeting the PIP'), list your current status — deliverables on track, metrics you're meeting, behavioral shifts you've made, and boundary negotiations from Day 19 that you've executed. Rate each item's strength 1-5. On the right ('Track B: Optionality'), list your status in each domain from Day 13 — financial actions taken, legal information gathered, professional conversations started, relational support activated. Rate each 1-5. At the bottom, set your energy allocation for next week: what percentage goes to each track? Check: is that allocation strategic (based on your Reading the Room assessment) or fear-driven? Write your energy allocation as a concrete plan: 'This week, I will spend [X]% of my non-work hours on Track A and [Y]% on Track B.' Block the time on your calendar.",
