    id: "jetstream-day-23",
    name: "Competence Anchoring + Saboteur Pushback",
    modality: "integrative",
    originator: "Albert Bandura (Self-Efficacy) / Mindcraft",
    primitive: "splitAnnotator",
    tags: ["core-jetstream"],
    dayNumber: 23,
    whyThis: "Before Week 4's deeper work begins, this exercise builds a floor under your feet. Albert Bandura's research on self-efficacy at Stanford found that the strongest predictor of future performance isn't talent or motivation — it's 'mastery experiences,' meaning concrete evidence that you've done something well before. Under PIP stress, that evidence gets buried. But evidence alone isn't enough. Your saboteur has a counter-argument for every accomplishment: 'That was easy.' 'Anyone could have done that.' 'That was a long time ago.' If you don't confront the dismissal directly, the evidence won't stick. This exercise adds a third column: for each accomplishment, write how your saboteur dismisses it, then write your one-sentence refutation. The refutation must be specific — not 'I'm good at my job' but 'Three people told me this launch wouldn't have happened without me.' You're building mental armor that is evidence-based and saboteur-tested.",
    instruction: "Each row has three columns. Left: a specific accomplishment or moment of competence. Middle: how your saboteur dismisses it (what the inner voice says to minimize it). Right: your one-sentence refutation — specific, concrete, inarguable. Aim for at least six entries. Tag each row by domain. When you're done, read the right column out loud. That's your counter-record. Choose the refutation that feels most stabilizing. Write it on a card or phone note. Before your next PIP check-in, read it once. This is not affirmation — it is evidence.",
