    whyThis: "Where did this pattern actually start? The saboteur you've been tracking didn't arrive with this PIP — it arrived much earlier. Somewhere you learned that evaluation means danger, that performance is the price of belonging. Murray Bowen's family systems research suggests these beliefs about authority and failure are transmitted across generations. The PIP activated an older script. Seeing the chain — from the original context to now — may help you separate the current-day PIP response from the historical activation. You're not resolving the old pattern in one exercise. You're seeing that your response has layers, and separating them changes how you respond.",
    instruction: "Build the chain from the bottom up. Level 1 ('The Original Context'): when did you first feel this way about evaluation? Not this PIP — the first time. What was the context? Who was the authority figure? What did you learn to do to survive? Level 2 ('The Reinforcement'): how did workplaces reinforce or reshape that original learning? What got rewarded? What got punished? Level 3 ('The Current Activation'): how does the old strategy show up now under PIP pressure? What's the same? What's different? When the chain is complete, look at the full picture: you are not the same person who developed that survival strategy. Name three capabilities you have now that you didn't have then. The next time the old pattern activates at work, try this: internally say 'That's the old script, not today's reality.' Then name one capability from your list that applies to this moment.",
