    whyThis: "This exercise brings together everything you've built over four weeks — NVC communication, saboteur awareness, boundary architecture, and Gottman's repair attempts — and focuses it on one conversation that matters. Day 26 is about preparation: writing three versions of that conversation so you can see clearly what the saboteur would produce, what your centered self would say, and what to do when things go sideways. This is different from Day 27 (tomorrow), which will simulate the conversation as a live dialogue. Today you write; tomorrow you practice. The three-version approach works because it makes the choice visible. When you can see the saboteur's version next to the centered version, the gap between them shows you exactly where your pattern wants to hijack the conversation — and the repair version gives you a way back when it inevitably does.",
    instruction: "Pick the conversation that matters most in the next week — PIP review, manager check-in, HR meeting, or a personal conversation carrying PIP stress. Write three versions in the panels. Panel 1 ('The Saboteur's Version'): what happens when your pattern runs the conversation unchecked? What does the Pleaser say? The Controller? The Avoider? Write it. Panel 2 ('The Centered Version'): rewrite using your full toolkit — NVC frame (observation, feeling, need, request), your boundaries from Day 19, your saboteur named and redirected. Panel 3 ('The Repair Version'): because conversations go sideways. Write your Gottman repair attempt ('I need to pause' or 'Can we back up?'), your self-soothing plan if you get flooded, and how you return to the centered version after a derail. Practice Panels 2 and 3 out loud. They need to live in your mouth, not just on paper.",
