    whyThis: "This program doesn't tie everything up neatly in 30 days. Some things will be resolved — patterns you now catch in real time, communication tools that feel natural, a clearer picture of the political landscape. Other things will still be open: the PIP outcome itself, a relationship that needs repair, a decision you're not ready to make, a saboteur pattern that's quieter but not gone. Pretending everything is handled would be dishonest. This exercise names what's still unresolved — clearly and without judgment. Research on 'open loops' in cognitive psychology suggests that unacknowledged unfinished business creates persistent cognitive load (sometimes called the Zeigarnik effect). Simply categorizing open threads — even without resolving them — may reduce that load by converting vague worry into organized awareness. Each thread gets a category and a concrete next step, even if that step is 'wait and see.'",
    instruction: "Each card represents an open thread — something unresolved from this program or your broader PIP situation. Sort them into four buckets: 'Needs More Time' (not urgent, will unfold naturally), 'Needs a Resource' (therapist, lawyer, financial advisor, career coach), 'Needs a Conversation' (something you've been avoiding saying to someone), and 'Needs Continued Practice' (a skill or pattern that's improving but not yet automatic). Use 'Add a card' to include your own open threads. For each card, click to add one concrete next step — not a plan, just the very next action. When you're done, look at the distribution. Most threads probably fall in 'Needs More Time' and 'Needs Continued Practice.' That's normal. The important ones are in 'Needs a Resource' and 'Needs a Conversation' — those need action, not time.",
