    dayNumber: 8,
    whyThis: "Most of us think we're good listeners — until we notice how much of the time we're actually planning what to say next. Otto Scharmer's Theory U framework (developed at MIT) describes four levels of listening that progressively deepen: Level 1 is 'downloading' — you hear what confirms what you already know. Level 2 is 'factual listening' — you open your mind to new data. Level 3 is 'empathic listening' — you open your heart and sense the other person's experience. Level 4 is 'generative listening' — you open your will and sense what's trying to emerge. Carl Rogers, the founder of person-centered therapy, demonstrated that empathic listening alone — being truly heard without judgment — is one of the most powerful catalysts for change. In a new role, your listening level determines the quality of information you receive. Level 1 gives you confirmation. Level 2 gives you facts. Level 3 gives you relationships. Each level has a distinct body signal, attention pattern, and type of information it captures. This exercise teaches you to recognize which level you're at and how to shift deeper.",
    instruction: "Each row represents a listening level. In the left column, you'll find what that level sounds and feels like — including the body signal that tells you you're there. In the right column, write about a recent conversation where you were at that level. What were you hearing? What were you missing? The goal is to notice your default level and practice shifting one level deeper in your next conversation. These skills feed directly into Day 10 (reading your manager) and Day 11 (reading colleagues).",
