    tags: ["core-basecamp"],
    dayNumber: 11,
    whyThis: "You don't need to become a different person for every colleague — but small adjustments in how you communicate can dramatically improve how your ideas land. Erin Meyer's research shows that communication mismatches are the #1 source of friction in new professional relationships. The issue isn't that one style is better — it's that people decode messages through their own style. When a direct communicator sends a message to someone who prefers diplomacy, the directness reads as aggression. When a relationship-first person emails a task-first person with three paragraphs of context before the ask, the task-first person stops reading after line two. This exercise asks you to map 3-5 key colleagues on five behavioral dimensions — not abstractly, but based on what you've actually observed. Each spectrum has concrete behavioral anchors at both ends so you're rating observable behavior, not personality traits. One adjustment per person is all you need to start.",
